In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims September 11th as Patriot Day and National Day of Service and Remembrance. He reflects on the tragic events of September 11, 2001, where nearly 3,000 individuals lost their lives in acts of terrorism. The President honors the courage and selflessness of first responders, servicemembers, and fellow citizens who served the nation during that time. He highlights the unity and resilience of the American people in the face of adversity. President Obama encourages Americans to participate in community service, emphasizing the importance of serving one's community and country. He calls for the flag of the United States to be displayed at half-staff and for appropriate ceremonies and activities to be held in remembrance of the victims. The President also requests a moment of silence at 8:46 a.m. eastern daylight time to honor the innocent victims of the attacks.